abstract: Impeachment will end in the Senate. It’s time to take up consensus issues.
snippet: Impeachment will end in the Senate. It’s time to take up consensus issues.
lead_paragraph: On Wednesday I will join a majority of my Senate colleagues in opposing the impeachment of President Trump brought by the House of Representatives.

headline_main: Why I’m Voting to Acquit President Trump

lead_paragraph: I am a Republican and former federal prosecutor who voted for Donald Trump in 2016. But I was deeply dismayed by the way his lawyers defended his misbegotten dealings with Ukraine during the Senate impeachment trial. Unlike Mr. Trump’s supporters, I believe the president might well be guilty of breaking the law.

abstract: Regardless of the Senate’s verdict, the impeachment inquiry, President Trump’s own words and other revelations yield a narrative establishing his involvement in the pressure campaign.
snippet: Regardless of the Senate’s verdict, the impeachment inquiry, President Trump’s own words and other revelations yield a narrative establishing his involvement in the pressure campaign.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When all the partisan posturing, parliamentary wrangling and legalistic arguing are stripped away, the impeachment process that dominated Washington for months produced a set of facts that is largely beyond dispute: The president of the United States pressured a foreign government to take actions aimed at his political opponents.

abstract: Buttigieg and Sanders were triumphant. But Trump had a few things he wanted to say for himself.
snippet: Buttigieg and Sanders were triumphant. But Trump had a few things he wanted to say for himself.
lead_paragraph: Bret Stephens: Just when I thought the Iowa caucus, and maybe the Democratic nomination, was in the bag for Bernie Sanders, Pete Buttigieg pulled out what looks to be either a largely unpredicted first-place finish in the Hawkeye State or at least a close second-place.

abstract: Michigan Gov. Gretchen Whitmer used Democrats' response to President Donald Trump's State of the Union address to swivel from impeachment to working-class voters' worries, saying her party is focusing on easing health care costs and other pocket-book concerns.
snippet: Michigan Gov. Gretchen Whitmer used Democrats' response to President Donald Trump's State of the Union address to swivel from impeachment to working-class voters' worries, saying her party is focusing on easing health care costs and other pocket-b...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Michigan Gov. Gretchen Whitmer used Democrats' response to President Donald Trump's State of the Union address to swivel from impeachment to working-class voters' worries, saying her party is focusing on easing health care costs and other pocket-book concerns.
headline_main: Democrats' Response to Trump Turns to Working-Class Worries
headline_print_headline: Democrats' Response to Trump Turns to Working-Class Worries
